### 2.3 Details of User Stories

#### Business Flow

**Step 1:** MCP server starts up and opens (or creates) the SQLite database at {workspace}/.code-intel/index.db

**Step 2:** Server checks if the modules table exists. If not, creates it with the full schema (including new pattern columns).

**Step 3:** If the table exists, server checks whether the new pattern columns are present (e.g., by querying PRAGMA table\_info(modules) or attempting a SELECT on the new columns).

**Step 4:** If columns are missing, server executes ALTER TABLE modules ADD COLUMN for each missing column with appropriate NULL defaults.

**Step 5:** Server proceeds with normal indexing operations. During module discovery and pattern detection, the detected patterns are written to the new columns.

**Step 6:** On subsequent queries (e.g., get\_module\_info MCP tool), the pattern metadata is included in the response, providing richer context to AI agents.

**Note:** The migration must be idempotent — running it multiple times on an already-migrated database must be safe (no errors, no data loss).

#### STORY 1: Persist Pattern Metadata in Modules Table

As a Code Intelligence server, I want to persist detected pattern metadata in the modules table so that patterns survive between sessions without re-detection.

**Requirement Details:**

1. Add 6 new columns to the modules table to store pattern metadata detected during code indexing
2. Each column stores a text value representing the detected pattern for that category
3. All new columns must be nullable (NULL default) to maintain backward compatibility
4. Pattern values are written during the indexing phase after pattern detection completes
5. Pattern values are read when serving module information via MCP tools

**Data Fields:**

|  |  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Field | Type | Required | Description | Example |
| di\_style | TEXT | No | Dependency injection style detected in the module | “constructor injection”, “field injection”, “none” |
| error\_handling | TEXT | No | Error handling pattern used in the module | “try-catch”, “Result type”, “exception handler”, “unknown” |
| naming\_convention | TEXT | No | Naming conventions detected from class/function names | "*Controller,* Service, \*Repository“,”unknown" |
| logging\_framework | TEXT | No | Logging framework detected from imports | “SLF4J”, “Log4j”, “console.log”, “unknown” |
| testing\_framework | TEXT | No | Testing framework detected from imports | “JUnit”, “Jest”, “pytest”, “vitest”, “unknown” |
| purpose | TEXT | No | Inferred purpose/responsibility of the module | “API layer”, “Business logic”, “Data access”, “Configuration” |

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. GIVEN a fresh workspace with no existing database WHEN the MCP server starts THEN the modules table is created with all 6 new columns included in the schema
2. GIVEN an existing database without the new columns WHEN the MCP server starts THEN the 6 new columns are added via ALTER TABLE without affecting existing data
3. GIVEN an existing database that already has the new columns WHEN the MCP server starts THEN no migration is attempted and no errors occur
4. GIVEN a module has been indexed with pattern detection WHEN the module record is written/updated THEN all 6 pattern fields are populated with detected values
5. GIVEN a module where a pattern cannot be detected WHEN the record is written THEN the corresponding column contains NULL or “unknown”

**Validation Rules:**

* Column values must be TEXT type (no length restriction in SQLite)
* NULL is acceptable for all new columns (no NOT NULL constraint)
* Values should be human-readable strings (not encoded/serialized objects)
* Maximum practical length: 255 characters per field (enforced at application level, not DB level)

**Error Handling:**

* If ALTER TABLE fails (e.g., disk full, permissions): Log error with full context, continue server startup without pattern persistence (graceful degradation)
* If PRAGMA table\_info fails: Assume columns don’t exist, attempt migration
* If writing pattern data fails for a specific module: Log warning, continue with other modules

#### STORY 2: Automatic Schema Migration on Startup

As a Code Intelligence server, I want automatic schema migration on startup so that existing databases are upgraded transparently.

**Requirement Details:**

1. Schema migration runs automatically during server initialization — no manual intervention required
2. Migration checks current schema state before applying changes (idempotent)
3. Migration uses SQLite’s ALTER TABLE ADD COLUMN which is safe and non-destructive
4. Migration logic must be implemented in all 6 server variants (Node.js, Python, Kotlin, Bash, PowerShell, CMD)
5. Migration should complete in under 100ms for typical databases (< 1000 modules)

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. GIVEN any of the 6 MCP server variants WHEN the server starts with an old-schema database THEN migration runs automatically without user action
2. GIVEN the migration has already been applied WHEN the server restarts THEN no duplicate column errors occur
3. GIVEN the migration is running WHEN it completes THEN a log message confirms successful migration with the number of columns added
4. GIVEN the migration fails WHEN the server continues startup THEN the server operates in degraded mode (reads existing columns, skips pattern writes)

**Validation Rules:**

* Migration must use ALTER TABLE modules ADD COLUMN <name> TEXT DEFAULT NULL syntax
* Migration must check column existence before adding (via PRAGMA table\_info or try/catch on ALTER)
* Migration must not use transactions that could lock the database for extended periods
* Migration must be safe to run concurrently (multiple server instances starting simultaneously)

**Error Handling:**

* SQLite “duplicate column name” error: Catch silently — column already exists, migration not needed
* Database locked error: Retry up to 3 times with 100ms backoff, then log warning and continue without migration
* Database file corruption: Log error, do not attempt migration, alert user

#### STORY 3: Backward Compatibility

As a Code Intelligence server, I want backward-compatible schema changes so that older databases remain readable without data loss.

**Requirement Details:**

1. Existing data in the modules table must not be modified or deleted during migration
2. New columns use NULL defaults — existing rows automatically have NULL for new columns
3. Application code must handle NULL values gracefully when reading pattern columns
4. Older server versions (without migration code) must still be able to read the database (they simply ignore unknown columns)
5. No breaking changes to existing MCP tool responses — new fields are additive only

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. GIVEN a database with existing module records WHEN migration adds new columns THEN all existing records retain their original values unchanged
2. GIVEN a module record with NULL pattern columns WHEN the MCP tool returns module info THEN NULL fields are either omitted from the response or returned as null/empty
3. GIVEN a newer database (with pattern columns) WHEN opened by an older server version (without migration code) THEN the older server reads existing columns without error
4. GIVEN the MCP tool get\_module\_info response WHEN pattern columns are populated THEN the response includes the new fields as additional properties

**Validation Rules:**

* No NOT NULL constraints on new columns
* No DEFAULT values other than NULL (to distinguish “not yet detected” from “detected as empty”)
* No foreign key constraints on new columns
* No column renames or type changes to existing columns

#### STORY 4: Consistent Schema Across All 6 Variants

As a DEV agent, I want all 6 MCP server variants to use the same extended schema so that behavior is consistent regardless of which variant is running.

**Requirement Details:**

1. All 6 variants (Node.js, Python, Kotlin, Bash, PowerShell, CMD) must implement the same schema extension
2. Column names, types, and defaults must be identical across all implementations
3. Migration logic must follow the same algorithm (check → add if missing → log)
4. Each variant’s schema file must be updated:
   * Node.js: db/schema.ts
   * Python: db.py
   * Kotlin: Schema.kt
   * Bash: lib/db.sh
   * PowerShell: code-intel-db.ps1
   * CMD: code-intel-scan.cmd

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. GIVEN any of the 6 variants WHEN creating a fresh database THEN the resulting schema is byte-for-byte identical (same column order, types, defaults)
2. GIVEN a database created by variant A WHEN opened by variant B THEN variant B can read and write all columns including pattern metadata
3. GIVEN all 6 variants WHEN their schema definitions are compared THEN the column definitions match exactly
4. GIVEN the migration runs on variant X WHEN the same database is opened by variant Y THEN variant Y detects no migration is needed

**Validation Rules:**

* Column order in CREATE TABLE must be: id, name, root\_path, language, file\_count, symbol\_count, last\_indexed, di\_style, error\_handling, naming\_convention, logging\_framework, testing\_framework, purpose
* All variants must use TEXT type for new columns (not VARCHAR, NVARCHAR, etc.)
* All variants must use DEFAULT NULL (not DEFAULT ’’ or DEFAULT ‘unknown’)

