## 5. Risks and Assumptions

### 5.1 Risks

|  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Risk | Impact | Likelihood | Mitigation |
| Schema migration fails on corrupted database | Medium | Low | Implement graceful degradation — server continues without pattern persistence |
| Concurrent server instances cause migration race condition | Low | Medium | SQLite handles concurrent ALTER TABLE safely; use try/catch for “duplicate column” errors |
| Inconsistent implementation across 6 variants | High | Medium | Define exact SQL statements in FSD; QA cross-variant testing |
| Large databases slow down startup due to migration check | Low | Low | PRAGMA table\_info is O(1) — negligible overhead |
| Future schema changes conflict with these columns | Low | Low | Use a versioned migration approach; document column semantics clearly |

### 5.2 Assumptions

* All 6 MCP server variants currently use the same modules table schema (id, name, root\_path, language, file\_count, symbol\_count, last\_indexed)
* SQLite version used by all variants supports ALTER TABLE ADD COLUMN (available since SQLite 3.2.0, 2005)
* The database file is stored locally at {workspace}/.code-intel/index.db and is not shared across network
* Pattern detection logic already exists and produces string values suitable for TEXT columns
* No other pending CRs modify the modules table schema simultaneously

## 6. Non-Functional Requirements

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Category | Requirement | Details |
| Performance | Migration must complete in < 100ms | ALTER TABLE ADD COLUMN in SQLite is O(1) — modifies schema only, not data |
| Performance | Pattern column reads must not degrade query performance | No indexes required initially; columns are read alongside existing data |
| Reliability | Migration must be idempotent | Running migration multiple times produces no errors and no data changes |
| Compatibility | Backward compatible with older server versions | Older versions ignore unknown columns; no breaking changes |
| Maintainability | Schema definition centralized per variant | Each variant has one authoritative schema file |
| Portability | Same schema across all 6 language implementations | Identical SQL DDL regardless of host language |

